T1  - PROMINENCE AND MARKET POWER: ASYMMETRIC OLIGOPOLY WITH SEQUENTIAL CONSUMER SEARCH
AU  - Hanazono, Makoto
AU  - Kudoh, Noritaka
Y1  - 2024/08/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12704
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1249
EP  - 1281
VL  - 65
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12704
Y2  - 2024/10/27
N2  - Abstract This article presents a new perspective on the nature of market power through the lens of firm prominence. We build a model of oligopolistic price competition with sequential consumer search, showing that a larger firm sets a higher price than its smaller competitors. Consumers are more likely to encounter sellers from a larger firm both immediately and in future interactions, resulting in less-elastic demand for that firm. Small firms can free-ride on the prominent firm's market power to raise their prices and earn higher profits. The Herfindahl?Hirschman Index provides a useful guide for welfare evaluation.
ER  - 

