T1  - MONETARY POLICY UNDER NATURAL DISASTER SHOCKS
AU  - Cantelmo, Alessandro
AU  - Fatouros, Nikos
AU  - Melina, Giovanni
AU  - Papageorgiou, Chris
Y1  - 2024/08/01
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12694
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 1441
EP  - 1497
VL  - 65
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12694
Y2  - 2024/10/27
N2  - Abstract With climate change increasing the frequency and intensity of natural disasters, what should central banks do in response to these catastrophic events? Looking at IMF reports for 34 disaster-years, which occurred in 16 disaster-prone countries from 1999 to 2017, reveals lack of any systematic approach adopted by monetary authorities in response to climate shocks. Using a small-open-economy New-Keynesian model with disaster shocks, we show that consistent with textbook theory, inflation targeting remains the welfare-optimal regime. Therefore, the best strategy for monetary authorities is to resist the impulse of accommodating in response to catastrophic natural disasters, and focus on price stability.
ER  - 

